sec.p:
Guidelines for timing the length of interactions were originally suggested by Howes and Mueller (1980), who used 5 second increments as a basis for determining interactions among non-verbal participants. Our observation period was lengthened, based on our observations in this population on the typical length of pause after speaking and potential topic change between participants’ exchanges. Timing began at the start of the interaction and continued until either (1) a pause of more than 10 seconds occurred between a resident interaction accompanied by a topic change or (2) a pause between participants of 30 seconds regardless of topic change. A codebook, established and refined throughout the study, was used to assign themes to interactions. Coders then labeled the interaction as:


‘friendly/positive’, in which there was positive and/or relevant verbal or non-verbal communication appropriate to the situation and/or the tone appeared to be pleasant;

‘unfriendly/negative’, in which the response of one or more participant was inappropriate or tone/reaction of at least one participant was unpleasant;

‘neutral’, when an interaction between two residents did not fit the criteria of either friendly/positive or unfriendly/negative and when the interaction contained no observable emotional reaction (such as when one resident asks another for the time) and/or a minimal exchange; or

‘more information needed’ when camera angle or field notes prevented adequate information for coding.
